award_description:
THE NEW YORK CITY COALITION AGAINST HUNGER (NYCCAH) IS SEEKING TO LAUNCH A TENTH YEAR OF ITS AMERICORPS*VISTA PROGRAM, THE CAPACITY-BUILDING AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE PROJECT. THIS PROJECT ENGAGES 10 AMERICORPS*VISTAS IN EFFECTIVE ANTI-POVERTY SERVICE BY PROVIDING ON-SITE CAPACITY BUILDING TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO ANTI-POVERTY ORGANIZATIONS THROUGHOUT THE FIVE BOROUGHS OF NEW YORK CITY. AS IN PREVIOUS YEARS OF THE CURRENT PROJECT, NYCCAH WILL PROVIDE COST-SHARE FUNDING FOR THREE OF THE VISTA MEMBERS. DURING THE 2011-2012 PROJECT YEAR, ONE VISTA WAS BASED AT NYCCAH HEADQUARTERS TO FURTHER BUILD CAPACITY IN VOLUNTEER MANAGEMENT PROGRAMS. A VISTA LEADER WAS ALSO BASED AT THE MAIN OFFICE AND WAS UTILIZED TO ASSIST WITH RECRUITING, TRAINING, AND TEAM-BUILDING. 

FOR THE CURRENT GRANT YEAR (2012-2013), TWO VISTA MEMBERS WILL BE BASED AT NYCCAH HEADQUARTERS. THESE POSITIONS INCLUDE: VISTA LEADER AND A VISTA WORKING WITH OUR VOLUNTEER DEPARTMENT.  NYCCAH WILL PLACE THE REMAINING NINE VISTAS DIRECTLY AT EMERGENCY FEEDING PROGRAMS (EFPS) -- FOOD PANTRIES AND SOUP KITCHENS -- OR CITYWIDE ANTI-HUNGER/ANTI-POVERTY ORGANIZATIONS THROUGHOUT THE FIVE BOROUGHS OF NEW YORK CITY. THESE VISTAS WILL PROVIDE CAPACITY-BUILDING HELP AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO THESE COMMUNITY-BASED AGENCIES TO BUILD SYSTEMS TO MORE EFFECTIVELY FIGHT POVERTY IN LOW-INCOME AREAS OF NEW YORK CITY. 

IN ITS FIRST HIGHLY SUCCESSFUL THREE-YEAR VISTA PROJECT (2002-2003, 2004-2005, AND 2005-2006), NYCCAH'S PRIMARY FOCUS FOR THE PROJECT WAS CREATING AND SUSTAINING "NEIGHBORHOOD NETWORKS" OF EMERGENCY FOOD PROVIDERS IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE VISTA HOST SITES. THE NETWORKS AIM TO: IMPROVE SOCIAL SERVICES IN LOW-INCOME NEIGHBORHOODS, REDUCE DUPLICATION, PROVIDE TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO SOUP KITCHENS AND FOOD PANTRIES, AND BRING KITCHENS AND PANTRIES TOGETHER FOR JOINT INITIATIVES AND COLLABORATIVE PROJECTS. FROM NYCCAH'S SECOND THREE-YEAR VISTA PROJECT ONWARD, THE PRIMARY FOCUS SHIFTED AWAY FROM NEIGHBORHOOD NETWORKS -- ALTHOUGH CREATING AND SUSTAINING "COMMUNITY CAPACITY-BUILDING CONSORTIUMS" IS STILL A MAJOR WORKPLAN COMPONENT AND THE VISTA TEAM IS WORKING TO EXPAND THE EFFECTIVENESS AND PROGRAMMING OF THESE NETWORKS -- TO BUILDING AND STRENGTHENING AGENCY CAPACITY THROUGH INTENSIVE, INDIVIDUALIZED, HIGH-QUALITY TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE. THIS WILL CONTINUE TO BE THE FOCUS IN THE UPCOMING 2012-2013 PROGRAM YEAR. 

FOR THE 2012-2013 VISTA PROGRAM YEAR, SOME VISTAS WILL BE PLACED AT NEW SITES WHILE OTHERS WILL BE PLACED AT SITES THAT HAVE PREVIOUSLY HOSTED VISTA MEMBERS AND HAVE FURTHER CAPACITY-BUILDING ASSISTANCE NEEDS. AS IN PREVIOUS PROJECT YEARS, NYCCAH WILL CONTINUE TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE BY SITE SUPERVISORS WITH ALL VISTA REGULATIONS SO ALL NYCCAH VISTA MEMBERS ARE WORKING TOWARDS THE ANTI-HUNGER POVERTY GOALS OF THE VISTA PROGRAM.

award_description: THE RECENT DECLINE IN THE ARCTIC SEA ICE  WHICH HAS REACHED HISTORIC LOWS  IS INFLUENCED BY BOTH ATMOSPHERIC AND OCEANIC PROCESSES THAT ARE WORTHY OF STUDY. RECENT STUDIES OF FLOODS OVER NORTH WESTERN INDIA AND ESPECIALLY PAKISTAN STRONGLY SUGGEST (LAU AND KIM 2011; HONG ET AL.  2011; ZHANG ET AL.  2012)  A WESTWARD EXTENSION OF THE MONSOONAL UPPER TROPOSPHERIC OUTFLOWS AT 200 HPA LEVEL WITH A WESTWARD SHIFT OF THE TIBETAN HIGH. TROPOSPHERIC HEAT AND MOISTURE TRANSPORTS FROM AROUND THE WESTERN FLANKS OF THE TIBETAN HIGH BRING WARM MOIST AIR TOWARDS CENTRAL ASIA NORTH OF THE HIMALAYAS THE UPPER ANTICYCLONE OF THE MONSOON IS THE WARMEST TROPOSPHERIC WEATHER FEATURES THE CIRCULATING AIR AROUND THE TIBETAN HIGH  DURING EPISODES OF HEAVY RAINS OVER THE NORTHWESTERN INDIA AND PAKISTAN REGION  DESCENDS NORTH OF THE HIMALAYAS WHERE THE SURFACE AIR TEMPERATURE HAS INCREASED BY NEARLY 5OC DURING A PRESENT DECADE COMPARED TO A PREVIOUS DECADE  ZHANG ET AL (2012)  THAT WARMING IS CONVEYED TO THE ARCTIC LATITUDES BY THE LARGE AMPLITUDE BAROCLINIC DISTURBANCES OF EURASIA. THOSE MERIDIONAL TRANSPORTS OF HEAT AND MOISTURE ARE IMPORTANT FOR OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE RECENT DECLINE OF THE ARCTIC SEA ICE. THE ATMOSPHERIC WIND DATA COVERAGE IS A MAJOR COMPONENT IN ALL SUCH TRANSPORT PROBLEMS. ZHANG ET AL ( 2012) SHOW MAJOR CONNECTION BETWEEN THE CENTRAL ASIAN SUFACE AIR WARMING REGION AND THE ARCTIC ICE MELT REGION VIA TRANSPORTS OF MOISTURE VIA THE SO CALLED ATMOSPHERIC MOIST RIVERS. WE PROPOSE TO EXAMINE THIS FEATURE FROM SEVERAL OBSERVATIONAL EPISODES AND MODELING.PRIOR TO THE LAUNCH OF A GLOBAL WIND LIDAR CARRYING SATELLITE  SUBORBITAL AIRCRAFT MISSIONS ESPECIALLY OVER THE NORTHERN ARABIAN SEA WOULD BE IMPORTANT TO MONITOR THE WESTWARD EXTENSION OF THE TIBETAN HIGH THAT CAN BE SEEN AS FAR SOUTH AS 15ON LATITUDE. THE ATMOSPHERIC STATE CAN BE DESCRIBED BY INVOKING PHYSICAL INITIALIZATION IN A GLOBAL FORECAST MODEL (KRISHNAMURTI ET.AL. 1991). IN PRINCIPLE IT WOULD BE POSSIBLE TO STUDY THE IMPACTS OF ENHANCING THE INITIAL MONSOON RAINFALL OVER THE NORTH WESTERN PARTS OF INDIA AND PAKISTAN BY 10- 40% SEQUENTIALLY IN A SERIES OF 10 DAY LONG FORECAST EXPERIMENTS. IN SUCH EXPERIMENTS WE SHALL KEEP TRACK OF MERIDIONAL TRANSPORTS OF HEAT AND MOISTURE ACROSS MIDDLE AND POLAR LATITUDES FROM 40ON TO 60ON. THE TIBETAN HIGH AND THE WINDS TO THE WEST OF THE TIBETAN HIGH CAN BE EXPECTED TO CHANGE IN THESE EXPERIMENTS.THIS PROPOSAL IS COGNIZANT OF THE PROPOSED OBSERVATIONAL CAPABILITIES OF CYGNSS AND PATH FOR SURFACE WINDS AND SURFACE FLUXES. THE DATA SETS FROM THOSE SATELLITES WOULD COMPLEMENT THE PROPOSED WORK SINCE PHYSICAL INITIALIZATION INVOKES BOUNDARY LAYER WINDS AND SURFACE FLUXES. IT IS OUR INTENTION TO DEVELOP THE NEXT VERSION OF PHYSICAL INITIALIZATION THAT WOULD EXPLOIT THE DATA SETS FROM CYGNESS  PATH AND A WIND LIDAR. WE ARE SUGGESTING THE MONSOONAL CONNECTION BASED THAT SHOWS THE MASSIVE MONSOON GYRE OF THE TIBETAN HIGH COMPLEX SITTING CLOSE TO THE SURFACE WARMING BELT OF CENTRAL ASIA. THE MODELING EXPERIMENTS WOULD THUS SUGGEST WHERE THE LARGEST CHANGES IN THE WINDS MAY BE NOTED. THE NORTHERN ARABIAN SEA  CURRENTLY LACKING UPPER AIR WIND OBSERVATIONS  IS A REGION THAT WOULD BE OF INTEREST FOR SUCH PLANETARY SCALE TELECONNECTIONS. WE ALSO PROSE TO INCLUDE DETAILED HEAT BUDGETS FOR THREE REGIONS THAT INCLUDE THE WESTERN FLANKS OF THE TIBETAN HIGH  THE CENTRAL ASIAN SURFACE WARMING REGION AND THE ARCTIC ICE MET REGION AND THEIR TELECONNECTIONS. IN OUR PROPOSAL THE MODELING RESULT WILL GIVE THE OBSERVATIONAL STRATEGIES FOR A SUBORBITAL AIRCRAFT RECONNAISSANCE CARRYING A WIND LIDAR. WE PROPOSE TO STUDY THE ROLE OF LIDAR BASED WIND OBSERVATIONS WOULD PLAY A MAJOR ROLE IN THE ABOVE SCENARIO.

award_description:
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
THE WIREGRASS RETIRED AND SENIOR VOLUNTEER PROGRAM IS A SELF-SPONSORED ORGANIZATION LOCATED IN THE FAR SOUTHEAST CORNER OF ALABAMA AND INCLUDES REPRESENTATION IN THE THREE COUNTY AREAS OF HOUSTON, GENEVA AND HENRY. 
ON APRIL 1,2014 WRSVP BEGAN THE SECOND YEAR OF A THREE YEAR GRANT CYCLE. ALTHOUGH WE HAVE BEEN ABLE TO MAINTAIN OUR PROGRAMMING WE HAVE MET SEVERAL SIGNIFICANT CHALLENGES THAT HAVE BEEN OUT OF OUR CONTROL. DUE TO ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES WE WERE FORCED AFTER THIRTY YEARS TO MOVE OUR OFFICE TO A NEW LOCATION. WHILE OUR NEW SPACE IS NEW AND VERY SUITABLE IT HAS TAKEN TIME TO REORGANIZE AND ADVERTISE OUR NEW LOCATIONS ADDRESS, TELEPHONE NUMBERS AND E-MAIL ADDRESS.
IN THE SPRING OF 2014 THE PROGRAM DIRECTORS SPOUSE EXPERIENCED A HEART ATTACK WHICH REQUIRED HER TO BE ABSENT FROM WORK FOR THREE TO FOUR WEEKS. IN JUNE OF 2014 THE ADMINISTRATIVE ASSISTANT RESIGNED DUE TO REOCCURRING HEALTH ISSUES.
SHORTLY THEREAFTER, THE JUVENILE COURT JUDGE WHO OVERSEES OUR JUVENILE TRUANCY PROJECT RESIGNED HIS JUDGESHIP TO BECOME JUDGE OF CRIMINAL COURT SERVICES. THE TRUANCY OFFICER WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF MENTAL HEALTH ASSIGNED TO ASSIST WITH THIS PROJECT RESIGNED TO RETURN TO HER HOMETOWN TO TAKE CARE OF HER AGING PARENTS.THIS LOSS LEFT OUR JUVENILE/TRUANCY PROJECT INOPERABLE FOR 4-5 MONTHS.
HOWEVER, TO DATE OUR PROJECT IS GETTING BACK ON TRACK. DUE TO THE STRONG LEADERSHIP OF OUR BOARD, STAFF AND VOLUNTEERS WE HAVE BEEN ABLE TO SUSTAIN OUR PROGRAM AND PROJECTS AS OUTLINED IN OUR GRANT APPLICATION.
AN ESTIMATED 341 UNDUPLICATED RETIRED AND SENIOR VOLUNTEERS WILL SERVE 24,466 UNDUPLICATED COMMUNITY INDIVIDUALS.  THEY WILL SERVE TO PROVIDE TRAINING IN DISASTER PREPAREDNESS, COMMUNITY BASED MENTORING FOR JUVENILES, TUTORING IN PUBLIC, SCHOOLS, ASSIST VETERANS WITH TRANSPORTATION AND OTHER ACTIVITIES, FOOD DISTRIBUTION THRU FOOD BANKS, FOOD PANTRY SUPPORT AND FOOD DELIVERY AND FOOD COLLECTION PROGRAMS, WILL PROVIDE TRANSPORTATION, MEALS AND COMPANIONSHIP TO THE SICK AND HOME-BOUND IN THEIR COMMUNITIES, AS WELL AS SERVE TO HELP THE NEEDS OF OTHER COMMUNITY PROJECTS THROUGH A NETWORK OF THIRTY-TWO (32) VOLUNTEER STATIONS SUCH AS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ADMINISTRATIONS, JUVENILE COURT SERVICES, VETERAN'S CLINIC, WIREGRASS AREA FOOD BANK, TWO LOCAL SCHOOLS, SOUTHEAST ALABAMA MEDICAL CENTER, THE HARBOR,  AMERICAN CANCER SOCIETY, AARP TAX AID FOR THE ELDERLY, CHRISTIAN MISSION FOOD DELIVERY, DIALYSIS CLINIC, WIREGRASS HABITAT FOR HUMANITY AND THE WIREGRASS UNITED WAY.  THE PRIMARY FOCUS AREA OF THIS PROJECT IS EDUCATION: K-12 SUCCESS TO ADDRESS JUVENILE TRUANCY.  AT THE END OF THE 12-MONTH PERFORMANCE PERIOD, ONE HUNDRED NINETY-FIVE (195) JUVENILE WILL HAVE BEEN MENTORED BY EIGHTY-FIVE (85) RSVP VOLUNTEERS. OF THIS NUMBER, 175 YOUTH WILL HAVE IMPROVED THEIR SCHOOL ATTENDANCE.  THE CORPORATION FOR NATIONAL SERVICE FEDERAL INVESTMENT WILL BE 84,814 WHICH WILL BE SUPPLEMENTED BY $130,323 OF NON-FEDERAL RESOURCES.

award_description: IN THE COLLISION-LESS MAGNETOSPHERE  THE DYNAMIC VARIABILITY OF ENERGETIC ELECTRONS IN THE RADIATION BELTS IS LARGELY CONTROLLED BY INTERACTIONS WITH PLASMA WAVES. CONSEQUENTLY ACCURATE MODELING OF RADIATION BELT VARIABILITY  IN RESPONSE TO CHANGE IN THE SOLAR WIND OR GEOMAGNETIC ACTIVITY  REQUIRES THE DEVELOPMENT OF GLOBAL MODELS FOR IMPORTANT MAGNETOSPHERIC WAVES. WE THEREFORE PROPOSE TO DEVELOP IMPROVED MODELS FOR THE GLOBAL DISTRIBUTION AND SPECTRAL PROPERTIES OF THREE IMPORTANT WAVES (CHORUS  PLASMASPHERIC HISS  AND EQUATORIAL MAGNETOSONIC WAVES) USING DATA FROM THEMIS  DE1 AND RBSP ONCE IT BECOMES AVAILABLE. WE WILL ALSO ATTEMPT TO IDENTIFY THE PARTICLE DISTRIBUTIONS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE WAVE EXCITATION. CHORUS IS AN ELECTROMAGNETIC EMISSION PRODUCED IN THE LOW-DENSITY REGION OUTSIDE THE PLASMAPAUSE  WHICH CAN CAUSE BOTH PRECIPITATION LOSS AND LOCAL ACCELERATION OF ENERGETIC ELECTRONS. DETAILED MODELING OF NIGHTSIDE CHORUS HAS ALREADY BEEN OBTAINED FROM CRRES DATA  BUT THE SATELLITE COVERAGE WAS EXTREMELY RESTRICTED ON THE DAYSIDE  AND MANY IMPORTANT PROPERTIES OF DAYSIDE CHORUS REMAIN POORLY ESTABLISHED. THE FIVE THEMIS SPACECRAFT HAVE EXCELLENT SPATIAL COVERAGE FOR OVER 3 YEARS OVER THE ENTIRE CHORUS SOURCE REGION. SPECIFICALLY THIS DATA WILL BE USED TO DEVELOP AN IMPROVED MODEL FOR DAYSIDE CHORUS  AND IDENTIFY THE MECHANISM FOR CHORUS EXCITATION. WE WILL ALSO MODEL THE PROPERTIES OF PLASMASPHERIC HISS  WHICH PROVIDES THE DOMINANT LOSS PROCESS FOR ENERGETIC ELECTRONS DURING QUIET PERIODS IN THE EXTENDED STORM RECOVERY PHASE  AND TEST THE PROPOSED ORIGIN OF HISS FROM CHORUS. EQUATORIAL MAGNETOSONIC WAVES MAY CONTRIBUTE TO LOCAL ELECTRON ACCELERATION  BUT OUR CURRENT UNDERSTANDING OF THE WAVE PROPERTIES IS LIMITED TO A VERY RESTRICTED RANGE OF L-SHELLS (CLUSTER) OR WAVE FREQUENCIES (CRRES). THE THEMIS DATA WILL ALLOW US TO DEVELOP A COMPREHENSIVE GLOBAL MODEL FOR THE POWER SPECTRAL INTENSITY OF THIS IMPORTANT EMISSION AND IT'S RELATIONSHIP TO ION RING DISTRIBUTIONS. THE IMPROVED WAVE MODELS WILL BE USED TO EVALUATE QUASI-LINEAR DIFFUSION RATES  WHICH CAN BE INCORPORATED INTO DYNAMIC MODELS OF THE RADIATION BELTS. THE PROPOSED RESEARCH ADDRESSES THE NASA STRATEGIC GOAL 3.2 LISTED IN THE 2007-2016 SCIENCE PLAN: UNDERSTAND THE SUN AND ITS EFFECTS ON EARTH AND THE SOLAR SYSTEM. IT ALSO ADDRESSES SEVERAL KEY SCIENTIFIC PROBLEMS IDENTIFIED IN THE 2009-2030 HELIOPHYSICS ROADMAP:1) UNDERSTAND THE FUNDAMENTAL PHYSICAL PROCESSES OF THE SPACE ENVIRONMENT FROM THE SUN TO EARTH.2) UNDERSTAND THE PLASMA PROCESSES THAT ACCELERATE AND TRANSPORT PARTICLES.3) UNDERSTAND CHANGES IN THE EARTH'S MAGNETOSPHERE  IONOSPHERE  AND UPPER ATMOSPHERE TO ENABLE SPECIFICATION  PREDICTION  AND MITIGATION OF THEIR EFFECTS.THE PROPOSED TOPICS FOR STUDY ARE DIRECTLY RELEVANT TO THE CURRENT NASA MISSIONS ON THE TIME HISTORY OF EVENTS AND MACROSCOPIC INTERACTIONS DURING SUBSTORMS (THEMIS) AND THE RADIATION BELT STORM PROBES (RBSP) OF THE LIVING WITH A STAR PROGRAM.

award_description: THE COMMUNITY ACTION COMMISSION OF BELMONT COUNTY SPONSORS THE RSVP PROGRAM IN BELMONT COUNTY. THE COMMUNITY ACTION COMMISSION WAS ESTABLISHED IN MAY OF 1965 AS A PART OF PRESIDENT LYNDON B. JOHNSON'S WAR ON POVERTY. SINCE THAT TIME, CAC HAS WORKED TOWARD ITS MISSION OF COMBATING POVERTY AND ITS CONSEQUENCES BY OFFERING PROGRAMS TO HELP OUR RESIDENTS BECOME SELF SUFFICIENT AND TO MEET THEIR NEEDS AND GOALS. CAC SEARCHES FOR VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES IN THE COMMUNITY WHICH SUPPORT OUR AGENCY MISSION AND MEET THE COMMUNITY NEEDS. VOLUNTEER STATIONS ARE DESIGNED TO HELP MANY DIFFERENT MEMBERS OF THE AREA INCLUDING LOW INCOME ADULTS AND THEIR CHILDREN, SENIORS, AND VETERANS.  A TOTAL OF 120 RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL BE RECRUITED TO SERVICE 14 LOCATIONS IN BELMONT COUNTY TO MEET A VARIETY OF NEEDS.  THE SERVICES THAT THE VOLUNTEERS WILL PROVIDE ASSISTANCE WITH INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING:  OHIO BENEFIT BANK FOR HOUSEHOLDS, OHIO BENEFIT BANK FOR VETERANS, PRESCHOOLS, HEAD STARTS, THE SUMMER FOOD PROGRAM, LOCAL FOOD PANTRIES, A COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY CLASS, AND A COMMUNITY GARDEN.  AT THESE SITES THE VOLUNTEERS WILL: ASSIST HOUSEHOLDS AND VETERANS WITH THE PREPARATION OF FILING THEIR TAXES AND DETERMINE IF THE CLIENTS ARE ELIGIBLE FOR OTHER COMMUNITY SERVICES; WORK WITH CHILDREN ON SCHOOL READINESS SKILLS; ASSIST WITH THE HEALTHY LIVING THEME AT THE SUMMER FOOD PROGRAM AND ENSURE THAT CHILDREN ARE MAKING HEALTHY FOOD CHOICES; ASSIST IN THE PICK UP AND DELIVERY OF FOOD AT THE FOOD PANTRIES; SUPPORT AND DEVELOP BASIC COMPUTER KNOWLEDGE TO HELP PREPARE ADULTS TO BE MORE MARKETABLE IN TODAY'S COMPETITIVE WORKPLACE; AND ASSIST FAMILIES TO CREATE AND MAINTAIN A COMMUNITY GARDEN.  AT THE END OF THE 12 MONTH PERIOD WE PLAN TO HAVE THESE EXPECTED OUTCOMES AT THE VOLUNTEER SITES:  OHIO BENEFIT BANK FOR HOUSEHOLDS WILL SERVE APPROXIMATELY 100 INDIVIDUALS AND FAMILIES USING 10 RSVP VOLUNTEERS.  OHIO BENEFIT BANK FOR VETERANS WILL SERVE APPROXIMATELY 20 VETERANS WITH TAX PREPARATION AS WELL AS HELPING THEM FIND INFORMATION ABOUT OTHER SERVICES IN WHICH THEY WILL QUALIFY. THIS VETERANS PROGRAM WILL USE 10 VOLUNTEERS. 12 VOLUNTEERS WILL ASSIST APPROXIMATELY 120 PRESCHOOL STUDENTS WITH SCHOOL READINESS SKILLS OVER THE COURSE OF A SCHOOL YEAR.  13 VOLUNTEERS WILL ASSIST APPROXIMATELY 220 BELMONT COUNTY HEAD START CHILDREN WITH SCHOOL READINESS SKILLS.  10 RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL SERVE APPROXIMATELY 320 HOURS OF SERVICE AT THE SUMMER FOOD SITES THROUGHOUT THE MONTHS OF JUNE, JULY, AND AUGUST PROVIDING CHILDREN WITH KNOWLEDGE FOR A HEALTHY FUTURE. 50 VOLUNTEERS WILL BE PLACED AT LOCAL FOOD PANTRIES THROUGHOUT THE COUNTY SPENDING UP TO 15 HOURS PER WEEK AT THE STATIONS. 5 VOLUNTEERS WILL SERVE 25 CLIENTS HELPING THEM LEARN BASIC COMPUTER SKILLS. 10 VOLUNTEERS WILL WORK CLOSELY WITH 20 FAMILIES TO BUILD A GARDEN THAT WILL MEET THE NEEDS OF LOCAL LOW INCOME FAMILIES.    THE CNCS FEDERAL INVESTMENT OF $32,668 WILL BE SUPPLEMENTED BY $_22 302 .(ANTICIPATED LEVEL OF NON-FEDERAL RESOURCES).

award_description:
MASSACHUSETTS CAMPUS COMPACT  (MACC) IS A STATE-WIDE COALITION OF OVER 70 COLLEGE AND UNIVERSITY PRESIDENTS COMMITTED TO DEVELOPING THE CIVIC SKILLS OF STUDENTS, BUILDING PARTNERSHIPS WITH THE COMMUNITY AND INTEGRATING CIVIC ENGAGEMENT WITH TEACHING AND RESEARCH.
MACC IS  DEDICATED TO FULFILLING THE CIVIC PURPOSES OF HIGHER EDUCATION. IN THE MIDST OF DIRE WARNINGS OF ECONOMIC AND CIVIC RECESSION, WE BELIEVE THERE IS GREAT PROMISE IN LEVERAGING THE POWER OF COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT TO FOSTER VITAL, VIBRANT, AND HEALTHY COMMUNITIES. MACC HAS A LONG HISTORY OF SUPPORTING CAMPUS-COMMUNITY PARTNERSHIPS, WITH THE KNOWLEDGE THAT THESE COLLABORATIONS HAVE THE ABILITY TO FOSTER CIVIC AND ECONOMIC CHANGE. CONNECTING ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT AND CIVIC ENGAGEMENT IN STRATEGIC WAYS ALLOWS MACC INSTITUTIONS TO HAVE A SUPPORT COMMUNITY RENEWAL ACROSS MASSACHUSETTS.
EACH YEAR, MACC SUPPORTS MEMBER INSTITUTIONS WITH PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT, ADVISING AND NETWORKING OPPORTUNITIES. THIS INCLUDES REGIONAL AND STATE-WIDE GATHERINGS, DEVELOPING AND DISTRIBUTING RESOURCES, AND PROVIDING INDIVIDUALIZED CONSULTING TO CAMPUSES. THESE EFFORTS FOCUS ON SUPPORTING CAMPUSES IN ENGAGING WITH COMMUNITY PARTNERS IN FOCUSED, DEDICATED, AND MEANINGFUL WAYS.
AS PART OF THE NATIONAL CAMPUS COMPACT NETWORK MACC IS ONE OF OVER 30 STATE OFFICES THAT COLLABORATE TO SUPPORT INNOVATIVE APPROACHES TO MOBILIZING HIGHER EDUCATION RESOURCES TO ADDRESS IMPORTANT COMMUNITY ISSUES ACROSS THE COUNTRY. 
THE MACC VISTA PROGRAM HAS BEEN SUCCESSFUL IN DEEPENING HIGHER EDUCATION'S IMPACT ON LOW-INCOME COMMUNITIES THROUGH A FOCUS ON THE DEVELOPMENT OF SUSTAINABLE INTERNAL SYSTEMS FOR CIVIC ENGAGEMENT AND THE DEVELOPMENT OF RECIPROCAL PARTNERSHIPS BETWEEN COLLEGES AND COMMUNITY-BASED ORGANIZATIONS. AS A RESULT OF MACC VISTA EFFORTS, THERE ARE MORE PARTNERSHIPS BETWEEN COMMUNITY-BASED ORGANIZATIONS AND COLLEGES AND UNIVERSITIES. THERE ARE MORE STUDENTS CIVICALLY ENGAGED IN THEIR COMMUNITIES THROUGH VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES, COMMUNITY SERVICE FEDERAL WORK-STUDY, AND SERVICE LEARNING PROGRAMS, AMONG OTHER THINGS.  OVERALL, THERE IS AN INCREASED CAPACITY FOR INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION TO CONTINUE TO SERVE COMMUNITIES IN MEANINGFUL WAYS. 

NON-PROFIT COMMUNITY BASED ORGANIZATIONS (CBOS) FACE A NUMBER OF CHALLENGES IN THEIR RESPECTIVE COMMUNITIES. THESE CAN INCLUDE AN INCREASING DEMAND FOR THEIR SERVICES THAT DOES NOT MATCH THEIR CAPACITY; FEWER RESOURCES; UNMET FUNDING NEEDS; AND INCREASING NEED FOR ASSESSMENT AND EVALUATION. DEVELOPING A PARTNERSHIP WITH A NEIGHBORING COLLEGE AND/OR UNIVERSITY CAN BE AN EFFECTIVE WAY TO RESPOND TO THESE CHALLENGES.

25 MACC AMERICORPS*VISTA MEMBERS WILL CONTINUE TO DEVELOP, BUILD, SUPPORT, AND DEEPEN CAMPUS-COMMUNITY PARTNERSHIPS FOR EDUCATION AND ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY. THESE PARTNERSHIPS WILL STRENGTHEN THE CAPACITY OF LOCAL ORGANIZATIONS TO ALLEVIATE POVERTY IN LOW-INCOME COMMUNITIES BY LEVERAGING THE RESOURCES OF HIGHER EDUCATION INSTITUTIONS. TO SUPPORT THIS SPECIFIC FOCUS, MACC AMERICORPS*VISTA MEMBERS MUST SPEND NO LESS THAN 25% OF THEIR TIME EMBEDDED IN THE COMMUNITY. AS A RESULT, INDIVIDUAL COMMUNITY BASED ORGANIZATIONS WILL BE BETTER ABLE TO FULFILL THEIR ORGANIZATIONAL MISSIONS AND DIRECTLY ADDRESS ISSUES THAT EFFECT THEIR CONSTITUENCIES, LOW-INCOME POPULATIONS THROUGHOUT MASSACHUSETTS.  STRATEGIC AND SUSTAINABLE RELATIONSHIPS AND PARTNERSHIPS BETWEEN COLLEGES AND COMMUNITY-BASED ORGANIZATIONS WILL RESULT IN A GREATER ALIGNMENT OF RESOURCES AND NEEDS BETWEEN PARTNERS, INCREASED NUMBERS OF STUDENTS AND FACULTY INVOLVED IN SERVICE TO LOCAL COMMUNITIES, SYSTEMS FOR THE TARGETED USE OF RESOURCES, AND MECHANISMS TO EVALUATE IMPACT OVER TIME. OVERALL, VISTA MEMBERS WILL BUILD CAPACITY AND SUSTAINABILITY OF THEIR ASSIGNED CAMPUS-COMMUNITY PARTNERSHIP(S) AND ITS WORK TO ADDRESS POVERTY AND POVERTY RELATED ISSUES.

IN DOING SO THE CENTER WILL ADOPT CORE ELEMENTS OF MOTIVATIONAL INTERVIEWING, SEEKING SAFETY, AND RESPECT AS EVIDENCE BASED-PRACTICES FOR ADDRESSING THE INTERSECTION OF SUBSTANCE ABUSE, HIV, AND VIOLENCE AGAINST WOMEN.

SINCE 1913, THE URBAN LEAGUE OF SPRINGFIELD (ULS) HAS FULFILLED ITS MISSION TO ADVOCATE FOR AND PROVIDE SERVICES TO ENHANCE THE ACADEMIC, ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL DEVELOPMENT OF YOUNG PEOPLE, FAMILIES, AND SENIORS THROUGH THE PROMOTION OF ECONOMIC SELF-SUFFICIENCY, QUALITY EDUCATION AND SOCIAL JUSTICE. IN FACT, THE URBAN LEAGUE IS CELEBRATING ITS CENTENNIAL BIRTHDAY OF 100 YEARS IN EXISTENCE.  ULS IS REQUESTING $650,950 TO PROVIDE SERVICES IN GRADES KINDERGARTEN THROUGH 12TH IN THE FOLLOWING CATEGORIES:  GED/DROPOUTS, PRE-ELEMENTARY DAY CARE, TUTORING AND CHILD (ELEMENTARY) LITERACY, ELEMENTARY EDUCATION, SPECIAL EDUCATION AND MENTORING THROUGH THE FOSTER GRANDPARENTS PROGRAM.
EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS/DISASTER RECOVER TRAINING WILL BE OFFERED TO ALL FGP VOLUNTEERS. THE PROGRAM WILL UTILIZE THE SKILLS OF 45 VOLUNTEERS TO PROVIDE TUTORING TO HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS, 10 VOLUNTEERS TO PROVIDE SUPPORT TO PRE-ELEMENTARY SCHOOL AGED CHILDREN; 35 VOLUNTEERS TO TUTOR/IMPROVE LITERACY IN K-4 STUDENTS; 40 VOLUNTEERS TO TUTOR IN AFTER SCHOOL PROGRAMS; 10 VOLUNTEERS TO PROVIDE SUPPORT TO SPECIAL EDUCATION STUDENTS AND 2 VOLUNTEERS TO MENTOR CHILDREN OF INCARCERATED PARENTS. THE FGP WILL CONTINUE TO BUILD SERVICES USING RESEARCH-BASED METHODS THAT PROVIDE TRAINING WHICH EFFECTIVELY DELIVERS SERVICES AND MAINTAINS A RESILIENT VOLUNTEER FORCE. STRONG PROGRAM MANAGEMENT AND PROGRAM EVALUATIONS WILL HELP ENSURE THAT COMMUNITY NEEDS ARE MET. OUTCOMES WILL INCLUDE IMPROVEMENTS IN SOCIAL SKILLS, LITERACY AND GRADUATION RATES FOR OVER 800 ECONOMICALLY DISADVANTAGED YOUNGSTERS, AS WELL AS DECREASED EMOTIONAL AND DISCIPLINARY PROBLEMS.

award_description:
ST. VINCENT HEALTHCARE, BILLINGS, MONTANA
ST. VINCENT HEALTHCARE WAS FOUNDED IN 1898 WITH A MISSION OF SERVING OTHERS, ESPECIALLY THOSE WHO ARE POOR OR VULNERABLE. THE FOSTER GRANDPARENT PROGRAM (FGP) SUPPORTS THIS MISSION, TARGETING AT-RISK YOUTH WHO HAVE BEEN IDENTIFIED AS BEING BELOW SOCIAL, DEVELOPMENTAL, OR ACADEMIC LEVELS.   53 VSYS ARE REQUESTED AT A COST OF $214,503 TO CONTINUE THE SERVICE THE FGP HAS PROVIDED FOR THE PAST 44 YEARS, IMPROVING SCHOOL READINESS AND PERFORMANCE AS MEASURED BY DETERMINED PERFORMANCE MEASURES.  ONE VSY WILL BE SPONSOR FUNDED. 
AN ESTIMATED 54 FGP VOLUNTEERS WILL SERVE AS MENTORS/TUTORS IN SCHOOLS, NON-PROFIT DAY CARE CENTERS, HEAD START CENTERS, AND EXTENDED TIME PROGRAMS THAT SERVE AT-RISK YOUTH THROUGH AFTER SCHOOL AND SUMMER PROGRAMS.  SOME OF THEIR ACTIVITIES WILL INCLUDE TUTORING STUDENTS IDENTIFIED BY SITE STAFF, WORKING WITH STUDENTS ON TEACHER ASSIGNED TASKS ONE-ON-ONE AND IN SMALL GROUPS, HELPING WITH CLASSROOM ASSIGNMENTS, READING TO OR WITH CHILDREN, AND PROVIDING ENCOURAGEMENT AND SUPPORT.  THE PRIMARY FOCUS IS TO IMPROVE SCHOOL READINESS AND K-12 SUCCESS FOR STUDENTS WHO ARE TESTING BELOW GRADE LEVEL.   ACCORDING TO STACY LEMELIN, PRINCIPAL OF MEADOWLARK ELEMENTARY IN BILLINGS, "FOSTER GRANDPARENTS ARE PART OF OUR INTERVENTION PLAN.  STUDENTS RARELY GET RETAINED WHEN THEY END THE SCHOOL YEAR BELOW GRADE LEVEL.  THEY ARE ADVANCED TO THE NEXT GRADE BUT ARE THEN ASSIGNED AN INTERVENTION PLAN THAT IS TARGETED TO FILL IN THE GAPS AND HOLES OF THEIR KNOWLEDGE.  THE FOSTER GRANDPARENTS FIT WELL WITH THIS PLAN AND ARE USED TO PROVIDE THE RICH LANGUAGE AND VOCABULARY THAT MANY OF OUR STUDENTS NEED.  STUDENTS WHO DO NOT GET THE EXTRA HELP THAT FOSTER GRANDPARENTS PROVIDE, ARE MORE LIKELY TO STRUGGLE AT THE NEXT GRADE LEVEL AND FALL FURTHER BEHIND. THE PROGRAM STRIVES TO BE A SUCCESSFUL INTERVENTION TOOL FOR OUR VOLUNTEER STATIONS AND THE STUDENTS SERVED BY FGS. "  
AT THE END OF THE 3-YEAR GRANT, WE ANTICIPATE THAT MORE THAN 486 STUDENTS WHO WERE IDENTIFIED BY TEACHING STAFF AS BEING BELOW LEVEL SOCIALLY, DEVELOPMENTALLY OR ACADEMICALLY, WILL HAVE IMPROVED LEVELS, WITH AT LEAST 162 STUDENTS BEING TARGETED BY FGS EACH YEAR.   THE CNCS FEDERAL YEARLY INVESTMENT OF $214,503 WILL BE SUPPLEMENTED BY $25,185 AS SPONSOR MATCH.

award_description: MOTIVATIONPROBLEM STATEMENT DERECHOS IS A NATURAL ADVANCEMENT OF THE EXISTING  HIGHLY SUCCESSFUL AUTOMATED EVENT SERVICE AES PROJECT. AES IS AN ADVANCED SYSTEM THAT FACILITATES EFFICIENT EXPLORATION AND ANALYSIS OF EARTH SCIENCE DATA. WHILE AES IS WELL SUITED FOR THE ORIGINAL PURPOSE OF SEARCHING FOR PHENOMENA IN REGULARLY GRIDDED DATA RE ANALYSES  TARGETED EXTENSIONS WOULD ENABLE A MUCH BROADER CLASS OF EARTH SCIENCE INVESTIGATIONS TO EXPLOIT THE PERFORMANCE AND FLEXIBILITY OF THIS SERVICE. WE PRESENT A RELEVANCY SCENARIO  EVENT BASED HYDRO METEOROLOGICAL SCIENCE DATA ANALYSIS  WHICH HIGHLIGHTS THE NEED FOR THESE FEATURES THAT WOULD MAXIMIZE THE POTENTIAL OF DERECHOS FOR SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH.  PROPOSED SOLUTION WE PROPOSE TO DEVELOP DERECHOS  AN EXTENSION OF AES  THAT 1. GENERALIZES THE UNDERLYING REPRESENTATION TO SUPPORT IRREGULARLY SPACED OBSERVATIONS SUCH AS POINT AND SWATH DATA  2. INCORPORATES APPROPRIATE REGRIDDING AND INTERPOLATION UTILITIES TO ENABLE ANALYSIS ACROSS DATA FROM DIFFERENT SOURCES  3. INTRODUCES NONLINEAR DIMENSIONALITY REDUCTION NDR TO FACILITATE IDENTIFICATION OF SCIENTIFIC RELATIONSHIPS AMONG HIGH DIMENSIONAL DATASETS  AND 4. INTEGRATES MOVING OBJECT DATABASE TECHNOLOGY TO IMPROVE TREATMENT OF CONTINUITY FOR THE EVENTS WITH COARSE REPRESENTATION IN TIME. WITH THESE FEATURES  DERECHOS WILL BECOME A POWERFUL ENVIRONMENT THAT IS APPROPRIATE FOR A VERY WIDE VARIETY OF EARTH SCIENCE ANALYSIS SCENARIOS.RESEARCH STRATEGY DERECHOS WILL BE CREATED BY INTEGRATING VARIOUS SEPARATELY DEVELOPED TECHNOLOGIES. IN MOST CASES THIS WILL REQUIRE SOME REIMPLEMENTATION TO EXPLOIT SCIDB  THE UNDERLYING DATABASE THAT HAS STRONG SUPPORT FOR MULTIDIMENSIONAL SCIENTIFIC DATA. WHERE POSSIBLE  SYNTHETIC DATAINPUTS WILL BE GENERATED TO FACILITATE INDEPENDENT TESTING OF NEW COMPONENTS. A SCIENTIFIC USE CASE WILL BE USED TO DERIVE SPECIFIC INTERFACE REQUIREMENTS AND TO DEMONSTRATE INTEGRATION SUCCESS. SIGNIFICANCE FRESHWATER RESOURCES ARE PREDICTED TO BE A MAJOR FOCUS OF CONTENTION AND CONFLICT IN THE 21ST CENTURY. THUS  HYDROMETEOROLOGY AND HYDROLOGY COMMUNITIES ARE PARTICULARLY ATTRACTED BY THE SUPERIOR RESEARCH PRODUCTIVITY THROUGH AES  WHICH HAS BEEN DEMONSTRATED FOR TWO REAL WORLD USE CASES. THIS INTEREST IS REFLECTED BY THE PARTICIPATION IN DERECHOS OF OUR ESTEEMED COLLABORATORS  WHO INCLUDE THE PROJECT SCIENTIST OF NASA SMAP  THE PRINCIPAL SCIENTIST OF NOAA MRMS  AND LEAD ALGORITHM DEVELOPERS OF NASA GPM. RELEVANCE TO THE PROGRAM ELEMENT THIS PROPOSAL RESPONDS TO THE CORE AIST PROGRAM TOPIC 2.1.3 DATA CENTRIC TECHNOLOGIES. DERECHOS SPECIFICALLY ADDRESSES THE REQUEST FOR BIG DATA ANALYTICS  INCLUDING TOOLS AND TECHNIQUES FOR DATA FUSION AND DATA MINING  APPLIED TO THE SUBSTANTIAL DATA AND METADATA THAT RESULT FROM EARTH SCIENCE OBSERVATION AND THE USE OF OTHER DATA CENTRIC TECHNOLOGIES. TRL ALTHOUGH AES WILL HAVE ACHIEVED AN EXIT TRL OF 5 BY THE START DATE OF THIS PROPOSED PROJECT  DERECHOS WILL HAVE AN ENTRY TRL OF 3 DUE TO THE NEW INNOVATIONS THAT HAVE NOT PREVIOUSLY BEEN IMPLEMENTED WITHIN THE UNDERLYING SCIDB DATABASE. WE EXPECT THAT DERECHOS WILL HAVE AN EXIT TRL OF 5 CORRESPONDING TO AN END TO END TEST OF THE FULL SYSTEM IN A RELEVANT ENVIRONMENT.

UNITED WAY OF GREATER TOPEKA (UWGT) IS PLEASED TO SPONSOR THE RSVP OF SHAWNEE AND DOUGLAS COUNTIES CNCS GRANT. UWGT IS A NON-PROFIT COMMUNITY-BASED ORGANIZATION WITH A VISION TO LIVE UNITED FOR THE COMMON GOOD. THE MISSION IS TO CREATE LONG-TERM SUSTAINABLE CHANGE IN OUR COMMUNITY. 
AN ESTIMATED 180 UNDUPLICATED RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL SUPPORT THE CNCS HEALTHY FUTURES FOCUS AREA WITH THE OBJECTIVES FOR 'AGING IN PLACE' AND 'OBESITY AND FOOD', AS WELL AS OTHER FOCUS AREAS; DISASTER SERVICES, ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY, AND EDUCATION. 
AGING IN PLACE VOLUNTEERS WILL DELIVER MEALS AND CONDUCT CLIENT SAFETY CHECKS, PROVIDE TRANSPORTATION AND COMPANIONSHIP. THIS ENABLES THE HOME-BOUND OR OLDER ADULTS, INDIVIDUALS WITH DISABILITIES AND TERMINALLY ILL PERSONS TO LIVE INDEPENDENTLY AND/OR TO EMPHASIZE THE QUALITY OF LIFE WHILE ATTENDING TO THE NEEDS OF THAT INDIVIDUAL IN THE FAMILIAR SURROUNDINGS OF HOME. 
OBESITY AND FOOD VOLUNTEERS WILL SERVE CLIENTS RECEIVING SERVICES THROUGH FOOD AND COMMODITY DISTRIBUTION PROGRAMS, FOOD BANKS, AND FOOD PANTRIES BY PACKAGING AND DISTRIBUTING FOOD, STOCKING SHELVES, REGISTERING & SERVING CLIENTS WHO ARE LOW-INCOME FAMILIES, PEOPLE WHO ARE UNEMPLOYED, UNDEREMPLOYED, UNINSURED AND OTHERS IN NEED OF EMERGENCY FOOD ASSISTANCE OR AT RISK FOR FOOD INSECURITY. THIS ACTIVITY WILL BE CONDUCTED THROUGH A NETWORK OF 12 VOLUNTEER STATIONS SUCH AS MEAL DELIVERY SERVICES, AND EMERGENCY FOOD BANKS & FOOD DISTRIBUTION AGENCIES. 
OVER 500 INDIVIDUALS WILL BE SERVED IN THE PRIMARY FOCUS AREA OF HEALTHY FUTURES. VOLUNTEERS WORKING TO SUPPORT THIS PROGRAM WILL INCREASE FOOD SECURITY FOR ADULTS AND FOR CHILDREN THAT WILL ALLEVIATE HEALTH AND OTHER ISSUES RELATED TO MALNUTRITION AND PROVIDE RELIEF FROM IMMEDIATE OR IMPENDING CRISES. THESE VOLUNTEERS WILL SAVE OUR COMMUNITY THOUSANDS OF DOLLARS. THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT ON AGING AND DISABILITY SERVICES HAS REPORTED AN AVERAGE ANNUAL SAVINGS OF $28,400 FOR SOMEONE RECEIVING MEDICAID SERVICES WHO REMAINS IN THEIR HOME INSTEAD OF ENTERING AN INSTITUTION. 
IN ADDITION TO THIS, HALF OF AMERICAN FAMILIES DON'T HAVE AN EMERGENCY PLAN IN CASE OF DISASTER. AMONG THOSE WITH A PLAN, 30 PERCENT LACK BASIC EMERGENCY SUPPLIES ACCORDING TO A SURVEY TAKEN BY THE NATIONAL CENTER FOR DISASTER PREPAREDNESS AT THE COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY MAILMAN SCHOOL OF PUBLIC HEALTH. RSVP DISASTER SERVICE VOLUNTEERS WILL ASSIST WITH OUTREACH ACTIVITIES TO RECRUIT AND RETAIN VOLUNTEERS TRAINED AND READY TO MOBILIZE IN THE EVENT OF DISASTER; EDUCATE AND TRAIN CITIZENS ON HOW TO BUILD DISASTER KITS, PROTECT THEIR HOMES, AND RECOVER AFTER A DISASTER; AND ASSIST WITH BUILDING AND REHABBING HOMES. 
THE UNEMPLOYMENT RATE IN TOPEKA IS 4.2% AND IN LAWRENCE 3.5% ACCORDING TO THE KANSAS LABOR INFORMATION CENTER, DECEMBER 2014. THE US CENSUS BUREAU REPORTS 17% OF PERSONS IN SHAWNEE COUNTY AND 19% IN DOUGLAS COUNTY ARE LIVING BELOW POVERTY LEVEL IN 2013. ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL WORK WITH CLIENTS VIA PHONE OR MEETINGS IN PERSON TO MENTOR THEM REGARDING FINANCES TO HELP GET THEM  ON A HEALTHIER MORE STABLE FINANCIAL FUTURE, AND PROVIDE TAX PREPARATION ASSISTANCE TO ELDERLY AND LOW INCOME FAMILIES DURING 4 MONTH TAX SEASON. 
ON AVERAGE, 55% OF SHAWNEE COUNTY CHILDREN ENTER KINDERGARTEN WITHOUT THE PRE-LITERACY SKILLS NEEDED TO BE SUCCESSFUL IN SCHOOL. ALMOST HALF OF THE CHILDREN ENTERING KINDERGARTEN IN LAWRENCE DON'T YET POSSESS THE SKILLS AND ABILITIES THEY MUST HAVE TO SUCCEED IN SCHOOL, SUCH AS SOCIAL, LANGUAGE AND EMOTIONAL DEVELOPMENT AND GENERAL KNOWLEDGE. FOR EVERY 50 CHILDREN WHO DON'T LEARN TO READ IN KINDERGARTEN 44 WILL STILL BE STRUGGLING IN THIRD GRADE. CHILDREN WITH BELOW-GRADE SKILLS BY 3RD GRADE ARE UNLIKELY TO GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL. IN ADDITION, WHEN CHILDREN ARE MENTORED ONCE A WEEK ON A REGULAR BASIS, A RECENT STUDY FOUND THEY HAVE INCREASED ACCOUNTABILITY AND RESPONSIBILITY. award_description: THE EARTH POLYCHROMATIC IMAGING CAMERA(EPIC) ONBOARD THE DEEP SPACE CLIMATE OBSERVATORY (DSCOVR) WILL MEASURE  FROM THE LIBRATION POINT 1  THE REFLECTANCE EMANATING FROM THE EARTH' SUNLIT DISK OF THE EARTH. OBSERVATIONS AT 10 WAVELENGTHS  FROM THE UV TO THE NEAR IR  AT A RESOLVABLE SIZE OF 24KM AT THE SUB-SATELLITE POINT WILL BE DOWNLOADED EVERY HOUR. WE PROPOSE THREE SETS OF AEROSOL-RELATED RESEARCH ACTIVITIES INVOLVING EPIC OBSERVATIONS. TIER-1 PRODUCTS CONSIST OF DIRECT USES OF EPIC DATA IN APPLICATIONS FOR WHICH THE COARSE SPATIAL RESOLUTION HAS LITTLE OR NO EFFECT  AND FOR WHICH ROBUST  DOCUMENTED INVERSION TECHNIQUES ARE AVAILABLE. THESE PRODUCTS ARE ABSORBING AEROSOL INDEX (AAI)  AND ABOVE-CLOUD-AEROSOL OPTICAL DEPTH (ACAOD). THESE PRODUCTS WILL BE AVAILABLE BY THE END OF THE FIRST YEAR.  TIER-2 APPLICATIONS  ON THE OTHER HAND  ARE THOSE THAT REQUIRE THE APPLICATION OF A RIGOROUS CLOUD MASK TO IDENTIFY CLOUD-FREE AREAS FOR ACCURATE RETRIEVAL OF AEROSOL PROPERTIES. WE WILL DEVELOP A FOUR-PARAMETER RETRIEVAL APPROACH USING A COMBINATION OF UV-VIS OBSERVATIONS TO DERIVE AEROSOL OPTICAL DEPTH (AOD)  ANGSTROM EXPONENT (AE)  NEAR UV SINGLE SCATTERING ALBEDO (SSA)  AND EFFECTIVE AEROSOL LAYER HEIGHT (ALH). ROBUST RETRIEVAL APPROACHES ARE AVAILABLE BUT IN ORDER TO ACHIEVE ACCURATE RESULTS  IT IS NECESSARY TO MAKE USE OF HIGH RESOLUTION LEO OBSERVATIONS TO BUILD RIGOROUS CLOUD MASKS TO OVERCOME THE SEVERE SUB-PIXEL CLOUD CONTAMINATION PROBLEM AT EPIC'S 24 KM RESOLUTION. WE ANTICIPATE THE AVAILABILITY OF THIS PRODUCT BY THE END OF THE SECOND YEAR.

award_description: TYPE IA SUPERNOVAE (SNE IA) ARE ONE OF THE PRIMARY TOOLS TO STUDY THE EXPANSION HISTORY OF THE UNIVERSE. THEIR USEFULNESS AS PRECISION STANDARD CANDLES IS LIMITED BY SEVERAL SYSTEMATIC UNCERTAINTIES AND THE POSSIBILITY THAT THE PROGENITOR SYSTEMS AND EXPLOSION DETAILS HAVE CHANGED OVER THE HISTORY OF THE UNIVERSE. OPTICAL OBSERVATIONS OF HIGH-REDSHIFT SNE PROBE REST-FRAME ULTRAVIOLET (UV) WAVELENGTHS  REQUIRING SPACE BASED OBSERVATIONS OF NEARBY SNE AGAINST WHICH TO COMPARE. THE SWIFT SATELLITE HAS ALREADY OBSERVED MORE SUPERNOVAE THAN ALL OTHER UV OBSERVATORIES COMBINED. WE PROPOSE TO CREATE AND MAKE PUBLICLY AVAILABLE A VALUE-ADDED ARCHIVE OF THE IMAGES AND PHOTOMETRY OF THE 200+ SNE OBSERVED IN THE UV BY SWIFT'S ULTRA-VIOLET/OPTICAL TELESCOPE (UVOT). WE WILL USE THIS DATA TO STUDY THE EFFECTS OF ENVIRONMENT AND EXTINCTION ON THE SN IA LIGHT CURVES. WE WILL ALSO COMPARE THIS LOCAL SAMPLE OF UV LIGHT CURVES WITH HIGH REDSHIFT SNE OBSERVED IN THE OPTICAL. THE SWIFT SN ARCHIVE WILL INCLUDE FINAL PHOTOMETRY AS WELL AS THE FINAL IMAGES APPROPRIATE FOR OTHERS TO USE TO PRODUCE THEIR OWN PHOTOMETRY OF THE SNE  OTHER TRANSIENT OBJECTS IN THE FIELDS  OR THE HOST GALAXIES. FOR EACH EPOCH OF PHOTOMETRY WE WILL ALSO COMPUTE THE SPECTRUM-DEPENDENT CORRECTIONS FOR EXTINCTION AND REDSHIFT. THESE DATA WILL BE USED TO MEASURE THE UV CONTRIBUTION TO THE BOLOMETRIC LIGHT CURVE AND LOOK FOR ANY TIME DEPENDENCE TO THE EXTINCTION. WITH THE LARGER SAMPLE AVAILABLE WE WILL LOOK FOR CORRELATIONS WITH HOST GALAXY PROPERTIES. WE WILL ALSO CREATE ABSOLUTE MAGNITUDE LIGHT CURVES OF SNE OF ALL TYPES FOR COMPARISON WITH EXISTING HIGH REDSHIFT OBSERVATIONS. THESE WILL ALSO BE USED TO MAKE PREDICTIONS FOR THE DETECTABILITY AND CLASSIFICATION OF HIGH REDSHIFT SNE IN THE REST-FRAME UV BY FUTURE GROUND AND SPACE-BASED TELESCOPES. THE SWIFT UV OBSERVATIONS FILL A CRITICAL NICHE IN OUR UNDERSTANDING OF SNE IA  AND THIS PROGRAM WILL ENHANCE THE SCIENTIFIC USE OF THIS IMPORTANT DATASET. THE WORK DONE AS A PART OF THIS PROGRAM AND USING THE CREATED DATA PRODUCTS WILL IMPROVE OUR UNDERSTANDING OF SNE IA AND THEIR USEFULNESS AS COSMOLOGICAL PROBES TO MEASURE THE EXPANSION HISTORY OF THE UNIVERSE AND UNDERSTAND THE NATURE OF DARK ENERGY. SWIFT HAS INVESTED THOUSANDS OF HOURS OBSERVING OVER TWO HUNDRED SNE. THIS PROPOSAL AIMS TO CAPITALIZE ON THAT INVESTMENT OF TIME BY PUBLICLY ARCHIVING THE DATA IN A FORM MORE USEFUL TO THE GENERAL COMMUNITY AND PROVIDING MULTI-WAVELENGTH PHOTOMETRY AND SPECTRUM DEPENDENT CORRECTION FACTORS. THIS WILL ALLOW THE SN COMMUNITY TO ADD THIS EXCELLENT UV DATA TO THEIR OWN DATA AND THEORETICAL STUDIES TO ENHANCE THEIR INVESTIGATIONS. THESE STUDIES WILL IMPROVE OUR USE OF THESE STANDARD CANDLES FOR MEASURING COSMIC DISTANCES AND THE EXPANSION HISTORY OF THE UNIVERSE. THIS SUPPORTS NASA'S STRATEGIC GOAL TO "DISCOVER THE ORIGIN  STRUCTURE  EVOLUTION  AND DESTINY OF THEUNIVERSE."

CURRENTLY WE HAVE 240 UNDUPLICATED RSVP VOLUNTEERS SERVING FOR THE PROGRAM.  THE VOLUNTEERS THAT ARE NOT SERVING IN THE PRIMARY FOCUS AREAS EMBRACE OTHER VOLUNTEER SERVICES WITH MANY OTHER COMMUNITY VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES.  ALMOST DAILY VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES PRESENT THEMSELVES AND FORTUNATELY ARE MET BY MANY SELFLESS INDIVIDUALS WILLING TO DEDICATE THEIR TIME AND ABILITIES REQUIRED FOR THESE CHALLENGES.  THE VOLUNTEERS IN FAYETTE AND NICHOLAS COUNTIES HELP TO FUND RAISE FOR THE AMERICAN CANCER SOCIETY RELAY FOR LIFE. IN WEBSTER AND GREENBRIER COUNTIES THEY CLEAN AND MAINTAIN THERE COUNTY ROADSIDE PARKS; POLICEMAN AND FIRE FIGHTERS VOLUNTEER THERE TIME FOR DISASTER PREPAREDNESS CLASSES PROMOTED BY RSVP AND OUR NEIGHBORHOOD WATCH GROUPS; LOCAL HISTORICAL SITES ARE PROMOTED AND MAINTAINED BY A DEDICATED GROUP OF VOLUNTEERS MOBILIZED THROUGH RSVP.  ALSO THEY WORK WITH OTHER COMMUNITY SERVICE ORIENTED PROGRAMS SUCH AS 4-H, AND BOY SCOUTS OF AMERICAN.  THE VOLUNTEERS WORKING WITH 4-H CAMPS TEACH CHILDREN COOKING, SEWING, CRAFTS, ETC.  SOME OF OUR OLDER MALE VOLUNTEERS ENJOY WORKING WITH SCOUTING.  IT GIVES THEM AN OPPORTUNITY TO PASS ALONG THEIR CAMPING AND BASIC SURVIVAL SKILLS TO BOYS WHO PROBABLY OTHERWISE WOULD NOT GET THIS ATTENTION. 
      60 RSVP UNDUPLICATED VOLUNTEERS WILL BE SERVING IN THE PRIMARY FOCUS AREA IN EDUCATION.  THEY WILL TUTOR OR MENTOR 160 STUDENTS WHICH INCLUDE TEENS, ELEMENTARY, AND HEAD START CHILDREN AT LOCAL SCHOOLS OR LIBRARIES TO IMPROVE THEIR SKILLS SO THEY WILL BE PROPORTIONED TO THE NEXT GRADE LEVEL AND SCHOOL READINESS. THE RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL ALSO BE POSITIVE ROLE MODELS TO THE CHILDREN AND IN RETURN HELP THEM WITH THEIR BEHAVIORAL, SOCIAL, AND EMOTIONAL PROBLEMS.  THERE ARE 21 STATIONS WHICH THEY WILL NETWORK WITH SUCH AS:  THE FOUR COUNTY BOARD OF EDUCATIONS, HEAD START PROGRAMS, AND CRAIGSVILLE, RONCEVERTE, AND SUMMERSVILLE PUBLIC LIBRARIES. THE PRIMARY FOCUS AREA OF THIS PROJECT IS EDUCATION.  AT THE END OF THE 12-MONTH PERFORMANCE PERIOD 60% OF THE CHILDREN WILL HAVE IMPROVED THEIR SKILLS TO BE PROMOTED TO THE NEXT GRADE LEVEL AND WILL BE SCHOOL READY. award_description: THE PROPOSED RESEARCH ADDRESSES TOPIC 5 - IMPROVING UNDERSTANDING OF CRYOGENIC PROPELLANTS. award_description: THE LEGAL NAME OF THE SPONSOR IS WESTCHESTER COMMUNITY OPPORTUNITY PROGRAM, INC. WHICH IS ALSO KNOWN AS WESTCOP. WESTCHESTER COMMUNITY OPPORTUNITY PROGRAM IS A PRIVATE, NOT-FOR-PROFIT, MUTI-PURPOSE SOCIAL SERVICE AGENCY OPERATING PROGRAMS TO COMBAT POVERTY AND ITS ADVERSE EFFECTS. WESTCOP'S MISSION IS TO MOBILIZE AND EFFECTIVELY MANAGE RESOURCES THAT WILL HELP THE LOW-INCOME AND AT- RISK POPULATIONS BECOME MORE SELF-SUFFICIENT. WESTCOP PROVIDES THE FOLLOWING PROGRAMS/SERVICES: HEAD START/EARLY CHILDHOOD EDUCATION, THE FOSTER GRANDPARENT PROGRAM, COMMUNITY ACTION PROGRAMS, SUPPORTIVE SERVICES FOR VETERANS AND  THEIR FAMILIES, VICTIMS ASSISTANCE, SUBSTANCE ABUSE, WEATHERIZATION, EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING AND OUTER LIMITS TRANSPORTATION. THE NUMBER OF VOLUNTEER SERVICE YEARS (VSYS) FOR THE FOSTER GRANDPARENT PROGRAM IS 172. THE DOLLAR AMOUNT REQUESTED IS $768,840 BEGINNING SEPTEMBER 30TH AND ENDING JUNE 30TH. THE SERVICE CATEGORIES ADDRESSED ARE HEAD START SCHOOL PREPAREDNESS, PRE-ELEMENTARY DAY CARE, ELEMENTARY EDUCATION, SPECIAL EDUCATION, AND OTHER HUMAN NEEDS. THE COMMUNITY NEEDS ADDRESSED BY THE PROJECT ARE THREEFOLD. THE TAX-FREE STIPEND ASSISTS WITH THE NEEDS OF THE LOW-INCOME SENIORS WHO ARE TRYING TO MEET THEIR BASIC FINANCIAL REQUIREMENTS WHILE RESIDING IN AREAS OF NEW YORK STATE THAT COMMAND A HIGH COST OF LIVING.  IT ENGAGES SENIOR CITIZENS IN A VOLUNTEER ACTIVITY WHICH HAS PROVEN TO SUPPORT SENIORS LIVING MORE INDEPENDENTLY AND LONGER IN THEIR COMMUNITY BY VOLUNTEERING.  AND THIRDLY, THE FOSTER GRANDPARENT PROGRAM WILL ENHANCE THE CAPACITY OF LOCAL SCHOOL DISTRICTS BY PROVIDING ONE-ON-ONE ASSISTANCE TO THEIR STUDENTS IN NEED OF EXTRA HELP WITH THE ANTICIPATED OUTCOME OF HIGHER TEST SCORES FOR THESE CHILDREN. THE RESEARCH BASED METHODS THE PROJECT WILL USE TO ADDRESS THESE OUTCOMES IS A DETAILED STUDENT ASSESSMENT FORM STATING THE CHILD'S EDUCATIONAL/SOCIAL/EMOTIONAL NEEDS AND TWO SUBSEQUENT PROGRESS REPORTS TO DETERMINE THEIR LEVEL OF IMPROVEMENT. THE PROJECT'S ANTICIPATED OUTCOMES WILL SHOW IMPROVEMENT IN A MINIMUM OF TWO SKILL AREAS THAT ARE IDENTIFIED BY THE TEACHER FOR 80% OF THE STUDENTS WORKING WITH A FOSTER GRANDPARENT VOLUNTEER. THE PROJECT WILL ALSO PROVIDE HELPFUL INFORMATION REGARDING ISSUES SURROUNDING THE AGING PROCESS AND REFERRALS FOR PERTINENT SENIOR SERVICES.

MISSION:  ACTION FOR EASTERN MONTANA IS COMMITTED TO STRENGTHENING AND ENHANCING THE QUALITY OF LIFE WITHIN THE COMMUNITIES WE SERVICE BY PROMOTING EDUCATION, ADVOCACY AND DIGNITY FOR ACHIEVING INDEPENDENCE.
ACTION FOR EASTERN MONTANA (AEM) HAS SPONSORED THE SENIOR COMPANION PROGRAM FOR 12 YEARS.  ESTABLISHED IN 1966 AEM IS A HUMAN RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL (HRDC) DESIGNATED TO SERVE 17 COUNTIES IN EASTERN MONTANA AS WELL AS THE NORTHERN CHEYENNE AND FORT PECK TRIBAL NATIONS.  AEM HAS 10 YEARS EXPERIENCE PROVIDING PROGRAMS AND SERVICES CENTERED ON IMPACT-BASED PROGRAMMING.
SCP PROJECT  FUNDING  SUPPORTS ONLY TWELVE EASTERN MONTANA COUNTIES AND THE FORT PECK RESERVATIONS  42 VSY SERVING AT 18 SITES ADDRESSING THE SENIOR INDEPENDENCE SERVICE CATEGORY.  SCP ADDS THE EQUIVALENT OF 21, FTE CARE GIVING PROFESSIONALS TO EASTERN MONTANA.
ACCORDING TO THE SUPERVISING SITES, THE 180 AT RISK SENIORS OR OTHER ADULTS WITH PHYSICAL DISABILITIES WOULD BE AT RISK OF PREMATURE INSTITUTIONALIZATION WITHOUT SENIOR COMPANIONS.   SITES HAVE EXPERIENCED A SIGNIFICANT INCREASE IN REFERRALS IN THE PAST 5 YEARS AS PEOPLE AGE AND CHRONIC HEALTH CONDITIONS OR DISABILITY PROGRESSES.

WE ARE REQUESTING $ 185,882.00 TO INCREASE OUR CLIENTS' ABILITY TO REMAIN IN THEIR OWN HOMES WITH THE SAME OR IMPROVED QUALITY OR LIFE FOR AS LONG AS POSSIBLE AS MEASURED BY INSTRUMENTS COMPLETED BY SERVICE SITE SUPERVISORS AND BY SURVEYING THE CLIENTS.  81% OF THE 180 CLIENTS SERVED BY SENIOR COMPANION UNDER THE PERFORMANCE MEASURES WILL RETAIN THEIR LEVEL OF INDEPENDENCE.

award_description: LEMOYNE-OWEN COLLEGE IS A HISTORICALLY BLACK COLLEGE (HBCU) THAT IS SITUATED ON A BEAUTIFULLY LANDSCAPED CAMPUS IN MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE. THE STUDENT BODY IS COMPRISED PRIMARILY OF AFRICAN AMERICAN STUDENTS WHO ARE CONSIDERED HIGH RISK FOR BEHAVIOR AND MENTAL HEALTH PROBLEMS, INCLUDING THOSE ASSOCIATED WITH SUICIDE AND SUICIDAL BEHAVIOR. LEMOYNE- OWEN COLLEGE IS KEENLY INTERESTED IN PROMOTING STUDENTS MENTAL HEALTH AND IN PREVENTING CAMPUS SUICIDES. TO THIS END, IT PROPOSES TO IMPLEMENT THE MAGICIANS STEPS (SUICIDETRAINING, EDUCATION, AND PREVENTION SERVICES) PROJECT, A COMPREHENSIVE AND COORDINATED CAMPUS SUICIDE PREVENTION INITIATIVE. THE PROGRAM CENTERS AROUND (1) CONDUCTING AN INSTITUTIONAL ASSESSMENT OF CAMPUS NEEDS, POLICIES AND RESOURCES REGARDING SUICIDE, SUICIDE PREVENTION AND OTHER MENTAL/BEHAVIORAL HEALTH CONCERNS IMPACTING STUDENTS PROGRESS AND SUCCESS; (2) EDUCATING STUDENTS, FACULTY, STAFF AND THE BROADER COLLEGE COMMUNITY (I.E., PARENTS, FAMILIES) ABOUT SUICIDE, MENTAL AND BEHAVIORAL HEALTH PROBLEMS (E.G., DEPRESSION AND SUBSTANCE ABUSE) ASSOCIATED WITH SUICIDE AS WELL AS PREVENTION AND INTERVENTION RESOURCES AND SERVICES AVAILABLE WITHIN LEMOYNE-OWENS COMMUNITY TO ADDRESS THESE PROBLEMS; (3) DEVELOPING AND IMPLEMENTING TRAINING IN THE ASSESSMENT, DIAGNOSIS, AND TREATMENT OF INDIVIDUALS SUFFERING WITH BEHAVIORAL/MENTAL HEALTH PROBLEMS (E.G., SUICIDAL IDEATION, DEPRESSION) FOR VARIOUS SEGMENTS OF THE CAMPUS, INCLUDING STUDENTS ENROLLED IN HELPING PROFESSIONS SUCH AS SOCIAL WORK; AND (4) EVALUATING THE EFFICACY OF THE VARIOUS EDUCATIONAL AND TRAINING ACTIVITIES, PROGRAMS AND SERVICES THAT WILL BE OFFERED AS PART OF THIS INITIATIVE, IN PROMOTING MENTAL HEALTH AND PREVENTING SUICIDE ON LEMOYNE-OWENS CAMPUS.

award_description:
THE PROPOSED PROJECT, OREGON ASSET BUILDING CORPS (OABC), THE MERCY CORPS NORTHWEST (MCNW) AMERICORPS VISTA PROGRAM, HAS A MISSION: TO BUILD THE ASSETS OF LOW INCOME INDIVIDUALS AND FAMILIES IN OREGON BY PLACING AND SUPPORTING VISTA MEMBERS AT HOST ORGANIZATIONS THAT WORK WITH LOW INCOME POPULATIONS. OABC VISTAS WILL FOCUS THEIR EFFORTS ON DEVELOPING OR EXPANDING PROGRAMS THAT DIRECTLY TARGET CYCLES OF INTER-GENERATIONAL POVERTY BY AMELIORATING DETERMINANTS OF POOR HEALTH, UNSTABLE HOUSING, AND UNEMPLOYMENT OR UNDER-EMPLOYMENT THROUGH INNOVATIVE, COST-EFFECTIVE, AND DATA-DRIVEN PROGRAMS FOCUSED ON CREATING EITHER ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITIES OR HEALTHY FUTURES FOR LOW INCOME POPULATIONS. 
WE HAVE TWO TRACKS TO OUR PROGRAM. THE FIRST IS FOR SITES INVOLVED IN ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY ACTIVITIES, WHICH INCLUDE SITES THAT ARE WORKING TO EXPAND INDIVIDUAL DEVELOPMENT ACCOUNTS, FINANCIAL LITERACY EDUCATIONAL OPPORTUNITIES, JOB SKILLS TRAINING, AND THE AVAILABILITY OF STABLE HOUSING.  THE SECOND TRACK SUPPORTS HEALTHY FUTURES INITIATIVES, ESPECIALLY FOOD SECURITY PROGRAMMING, WELLNESS EDUCATION, DISEASE PREVENTION, AND HEALTHCARE ACCESS.  LASTLY, WE ARE ALSO LOOKING TO SERVE THOSE LIVING IN PARTICULARLY DISTRESSED URBAN AND MINORITY COMMUNITIES AND DISTRESSED COMMUNITIES IN RURAL OREGON. 
THIS PROJECT IS IN DIRECT ALIGNMENT WITH THE CNCS STRATEGIC PLAN AND 2014 VISTA PROGRAMMING GUIDANCE; THE OREGON ASSET BUILDING CORPS WILL WORK TO INCREASE THE LONG-TERM CAPACITY OF LOW INCOME COMMUNITIES AND PERSONS BY SUPPORTING THEM IN ATTAINING SKILLS, HARD ASSETS, EDUCATION, OR PHYSICAL WELLNESS, THEREBY INCREASING QUALITY OF LIFE AS WELL AS THE ABILITY OF THE EFFECTED PERSONS TO ACCRUE ASSETS OR SKILLS THAT WILL MOVE THEM OUT OF POVERTY AND ENCOURAGE A CONTINUED ECONOMIC WELL-BEING AND HEALTH. ADDITIONALLY, OUR PROGRAM WILL PLACE VISTAS IN PROJECTS THAT ARE COMMUNITY ORIENTED AND INNOVATIVE, PROGRAMS THAT CLEARLY EXPAND AN ORGANIZATION'S EFFORTS IN A QUANTIFIABLE FASHION.  HOST ORGANIZATIONS ARE HIGH-IMPACT AND FOCUSED ON CREATING SUSTAINABLE SOLUTIONS TO VARIETY OF LOCAL PROBLEMS. SOME OF OUR VISTA PROJECTS ARE IMPLEMENTING OTHER COMPONENTS OF THE FOCUS AREA HEALTHY FUTURES AS AN ACTIVITY TO ASSISTING LOW INCOME OREGONIANS IN ACCESSING A HEALTHIER FINANCIAL LIFESTYLE.   
FOR FY 2014, MCNW IS REQUESTING 14 MEMBERS AND 1 VISTA LEADER. THE COHORT OF 14 VISTA VOLUNTEERS AND THE VISTA LEADER WILL BE ENGAGED FOR 12 MONTHS.
MERCY CORPS NORTHWEST IS THE ASSUMED BUSINESS NAME FOR THE 501(C)3 NON-PROFIT, MERCY ENTERPRISE CORPORATION.  THE ORGANIZATION WAS ESTABLISHED IN 1998 AS A PROGRAM OF MERCY CORPS, THE PORTLAND-BASED INTERNATIONAL RELIEF AND DEVELOPMENT AGENCY AND IS ITS ONLY DOMESTIC PROGRAM.  IN 2002, MERCY CORPS NORTHWEST RECEIVED U.S. TREASURY DESIGNATION AS A COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT FINANCIAL INSTITUTION (CDFI).  MCNW IS SUPPORTED BY THE SERVICE OF NINE BOARD MEMBERS, ALL DEDICATED TO THE PACIFIC NORTHWEST AND THE MISSION OF THE ORGANIZATION.  MCNW EMPLOYS A STAFF OF 21, STUDENT INTERNS, UNIVERSITY PROJECT TEAMS AND MANY VOLUNTEERS.  STAFF LANGUAGE SKILLS INCLUDE RUSSIAN AND FRENCH.   
MCNW ASSISTS LOW-INCOME POPULATIONS IN OREGON AND WASHINGTON BY INCREASING THEIR ECONOMIC SELF-SUFFICIENCY AND COMMUNITY INTEGRATION THROUGH MICROENTERPRISE DEVELOPMENT AND SELF-EMPLOYMENT.  OUR MISSION PROVIDES A DOMESTIC CONTEXT TO THE PARALLEL MISSION OF OUR PARENT, MERCY CORPS, WHICH IS TO ALLEVIATE SUFFERING, POVERTY AND OPPRESSION BY HELPING PEOPLE BUILD SECURE, PRODUCTIVE AND JUST COMMUNITIES.  WE VALUE THE POTENTIAL OF PEOPLE TO IMPROVE THEIR LIVES AND GAIN INDEPENDENCE. WE BUILD PROGRAMS THAT ADDRESS THE ROOTS OF PERSISTENT ECONOMIC HARDSHIP BY DESIGNING APPROACHES THAT ADDRESS POPULATIONS THAT HAVE BEEN TRAPPED IN POVERTY AND INTER-GENERATIONAL CYCLES OF ECONOMIC NEED.

award_description:
SIENA COLLEGE IS A COEDUCATIONAL, INDEPENDENT LIBERAL ARTS COLLEGE IN THE CATHOLIC AND FRANCISCAN TRADITION. THE MISSION OF THE COLLEGE IS TO CREATE A LEARNING COMMUNITY THAT IS STUDENT-CENTERED AND FOSTERS RIGOROUS INTELLECTUAL DEVELOPMENT THROUGH A HEALTHY EXCHANGE OF IDEAS BOTH INSIDE AND OUTSIDE THE CLASSROOM. SIENA COLLEGE IS GUIDED BY THE TEACHINGS OF ST. FRANCIS OF ASSISI, SPECIFICALLY, SERVICE AMONG THE POOR AND MARGINALIZED. THE MARRIAGE OF ACADEMICS AND SERVICE DISTINGUISHES SIENA COLLEGE FROM OTHER COLLEGES IN THE AREA. SIENA IDENTIFIES ITSELF AS AN ACADEMIC SERVICE LEARNING INSTITUTION THAT SEEKS TO EMPOWER POOR COMMUNITIES THROUGH SERVICE WITH THOSE COMMUNITIES.  IN 2008, THE OFFICE OF ACADEMIC COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT (ACE) WAS ESTABLISHED WITH THE GOAL OF IMPLEMENTING  THE DEEP SERVICE PARTNERSHIP MODEL AND DEVELOPING A BRIDGE BETWEEN THE COMMUNITY AND CAMPUS RESOURCES FOR THE FIGHTING  POVERTY IN THE CAPITAL REGION. THE OFFICE OF ACADEMIC COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT (ACE) INCLUDES THE SIENA BONNER SERVICE LEADERS PROGRAM (AN AMERICORPS NATIONAL PROGRAM ADMINISTERED THROUGH THE BONNER FOUNDATION), THE ACADEMIC AMERICORPS PROGRAM, THE SUMMER SERVICE SCHOLARS PROGRAM (VISTA AND AMERICORPS FUNDED SUMMER INTERNSHIPS) PREVIOUSLY KNOWN AS THE SUMMER SERVICE ASSOCIATES PROGRAM, THE ACADEMIC SERVICE LEARNING AND COMMUNITY BASED RESEARCH PROGRAM, THE CIVIC ENGAGEMENT CAMP AND THE SIENA AMERICORPS VISTA FELLOWS PROGRAM. WITH CNCS ASSISTANCE AND PARTNERSHIP, SIENA COLLEGE TRANSFORMS A ONE MILLION DOLLAR INVESTMENT MORE THAN 2.75 MILLION DOLLARS OF IMPACT ANNUALLY WITHIN THE CAPITAL REGION OF NY.

PROJECT ACTIVITIES OF VISTA POSITIONS INCLUDE: PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT AND SUSTAINABILITY, VOLUNTEER RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION, DEVELOPMENT OF VOLUNTEER TRAINING AND TRACKING SYSTEMS, DEVELOPMENT OF COMMUNITY PARTNER RELATIONSHIPS, FUNDING RESEARCH THROUGH PARTICIPATION IN GRANT ACTIVITIES AND PARTICIPATION ON A COLLEGE WIDE TEAM TO BUILD INSTITUTIONAL CAPACITY AND EXPERTISE IN VOLUNTEER TRAINING, PROVISION, OUTCOME MEASURESMENTS AND PROGRAM IMPLEMENTATION IN BOTH CURRICULAR AND CO-CURRICULAR ACTIVITIES OF THE COLLEGE.

ON-CAMPUS VISTA FELLOWS WORK WITH A PARTICULAR OFFICE OR DEPARTMENT TO CREATE AND/OR BUILD THE CAPACITY OF THE OFFICE TO ADDRESS POVERTY IN OUR COMMUNITY. THESE FELLOWS ARE TRAINED TO BUILD BRIDGES BETWEEN THE OFFICE THEY SERVE AND COMMUNITY PARTNER AGENCIES. RESOURCE DEVELOPMENT, VOLUNTEER DEVELOPMENT, PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT, DEVELOPMENT OF COMMUNITY-BASED RESEARCH AND ACADEMIC SERVICE LEARNING CAPABILITIES AND PARTNERSHIPS ARE THE PRIMARY ACTIVITIES OF THESE VISTAS.  

OFF-CAMPUS VISTA FELLOWS ARE PLACED IN A COMMUNITY PARTNER AGENCY THAT HAS DEVELOPED A THREE-YEAR JOB PLAN OUTLINING AN INCREASINGLY SOPHISTICATED PARTNERSHIP WITH SIENA'S DEEP SERVICE APPROACH THROUGH THE VISTA PLACEMENT.  PART OF THIS THREE-YEAR PLANNING PROCESS IS THE DESIGN OF A VAD FOR A POTENTIAL VISTA PLACEMENT.  VISTA FELLOWS ON THIS TEAM WORK TO BUILD THE CAPACITY OF THEIR SITE AGENCY TO ADDRESS POVERTY, IN PART BY BUILDING THE PARTNERSHIP POTENTIAL BETWEEN SIENA AND THE COMMUNITY PARTNER.  VISTA FELLOWS FUNCTION AS A TEAM: THEY MEET AT LEAST TWICE PER MONTH AS A STAFF TO REPORT PROGRESS AND BRAINSTORM COLLABORATIVE OPPORTUNITIES; BUILD CONNECTING PROJECTS BETWEEN COMMUNITY PARTNER AGENCIES, BETWEEN COMMUNITY PARTNERS AND SIENA COLLEGE, AND BETWEEN COMMUNITY PARTNERS AND COMMUNITY MEMBERS; PARTICIPATE IN PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT OPPORTUNITIES TOGETHER; PARTICIPATE IN AN ACADEMIC ENRICHMENT PROGRAM TOGETHER; AND ARE TRAINED TO THINK ABOUT THEMSELVES AS SIENA VISTA FELLOWS WORKING TOGETHER ON A TEAM.

award_description: WE PROPOSE TO EXPLORE CORE STRUCTURE OF HORIZONTAL BRANCH STARS BY APPLYING ASTEROSEISMOLOGICAL TOOLS TO KEPLER DATA OF EXTREME HORIZONTAL BRANCH (SPECTRAL CLASS SUBDWARF B) STARS. SUBDWARF B (SDB) STARS ARE THE ATMOSPHERE-STRIPPED CORES OF HORIZONTAL BRANCH STARS. MANY HAPPEN TO PULSATE  AND THAT ALLOWS US TO PROBE THEIR STRUCTURE. FROM KEPLER'S MAIN MISSION  WE LEARNED HOW TO IDENTIFY PULSATION MODES AND TO CONSTRAIN STRUCTURE MODELS FROM PERIOD SPACINGS AND FREQUENCY MULTIPLETS. PERIOD SPACINGS ALSO HELP TO DISCERN INTERNAL STRUCTURE AND AGE SINCE SOME STARS SHOW SUBSTANTIAL MODE TRAPPING WHILE IN OTHERS IT APPEARS TO BE ABSENT. THE AMOUNT (AND LOCATION) OF THE MODE TRAPPING SEQUENCE IS A FUNCTION OF THE CORE STRUCTURE WHICH EVOLVES WITH TIME. BY SAMPLING SDB STARS OF DIFFERENT EVOLUTIONARY AGE AND ENVELOPE MASS  WE CAN USE THE SMALL DEVIATIONS OF PERIOD SPACINGS TO CONSTRAIN STRUCTURE MODELS.FREQUENCY MULTIPLETS ALSO TELL US THE ROTATION PERIOD AND ORIENTATION OF THE PULSATION AXIS. FROM THIS INFORMATION WE HAVE DISCOVERED THAT ROTATION PERIODS ARE LONG (20-100 DAYS)  EVEN FOR STARS WITH BINARY PERIOD DOWN TO 0.4 DAYS. THIS IS A SURPRISING RESULT AS IT HAS BEEN ASSUMED THAT CLOSE BINARIES QUICKLY TIDALLY LOCK THEIR COMPONENTS.WE MADE SIGNIFICANT PROGRESS FROM THE ORIGINAL KEPLER MISSION. HOWEVER  TO FULLY EXPLOIT THOSE ADVANCES  WE NEED TO COMPLETE THE CHARACTERIZATION OF HELIUM-FUSING CORES ACROSS THEIR RANGE OF AGE (FROM ZERO-AGE TO TERMINAL-AGE ON THE HORIZONTAL BRANCH) AND TEMPERATURE (AN INDICATOR OF THE ENVELOPE-TO-CORE MASS RATIO). IT WOULD ALSO BE A HUGE BENEFIT TO HAVE MORE EXAMPLES OF PULSATORS IN BINARIES  AS THAT ALLOWS US TO FURTHER EXPLORE HOW ANGULAR MOMENTUM IS CONSERVED AND/OR TRANSFERRED DURING ENVELOPE EJECTION.TO CONTINUE WORKING TOWARD A COMPLETE UNDERSTANDING OF HORIZONTAL BRANCH CORES (INCLUDING MASS LOSS AND POST-HELIUM-FLASH EVOLUTION)  WE ARE PROPOSING THAT K2 OBTAIN SHORT-CADENCE (SC) OBSERVATIONS OF A SELECTION OF LIKELY SDB PULSATORS AND LONG-CADENCE (LC) OBSERVATIONS OF REMAINING SDB STARS. THE SC DATA CAN FULLY EXPLORE PULSATIONS AND SHORT-PERIOD (1 DAY) BINARIES AND WHILE THE LC DATA CAN DETECT SOME PULSATIONS WHILE STILL EXPLORING BINARY SDB STARS  ESPECIALLY THE LONGER-PERIOD ONES.OUR TEAM HAS EXTENSIVELY EXPLORED MANY ASPECTS OF SDB STARS  INCLUDING SPECTROSCOPIC CHARACTERIZATION  BINARY PROPERTIES  AND THE APPLICATION OF ASTEROSEISMIC TOOLS. WE HAVE BEEN EXAMINING SDB STARS SINCE THEIR PULSATIONS WERE DISCOVERED IN 1996 AND HAVE PUBLISHED OVER 20 PAPERS FROM KEPLER'S MAIN MISSION.WE HAVE ALSO INCORPORATED STUDENTS INTO OUR WORK. MANY OF OUR PAPERS INCLUDE GRADUATE AND UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS AS SIGNIFICANT CONTRIBUTORS. MISSOURI STATE UNIVERSITY DOES NOT HAVE A GRADUATE PROGRAM  AND AS A RESULT  UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS HAVE LEARNED TO PROCESS  ANALYZE  AND INTERPRET NASA SATELLITE DATA TO DETECT PULSATIONS AND SIGNATURES OF BINARITY. THEY HAVE ALSO BEEN INVOLVED IN PRE- AND POST-KEPLER CHARACTERIZATION STUDIES  PROVIDING THEM WITH A BROAD RANGE OF TRAINING.

award_description: WE SEEK TO UNDERSTAND THE CONDITIONS AND DYNAMICS OF THE EARLIEST STAGES OF PLANETARY SYSTEM FORMATION THROUGH A STUDY OF THE VARIABILITY OF YOUNG STARS IN THE K2 CAMPAIGN-4 FIELD OF VIEW. WE PROPOSE TO OBSERVE AT LONG CADENCE -50 YOUNG STELLAR OBJECTS  TTAURI STARS  PRE-MAIN SEQUENCE STARS  AND FLARE STARS SELECTED FROM THE LITERATURE AND ASSOCIATED WITH THE PLEIADES AND HYADES STAR CLUSTERS. THE OBJECTS RANGE IN AGE FROM TENS TO HUNDREDS OF MILLION YEARS AND IN SPECTRAL TYPE FROM LATE-F THROUGH MID-M. WE WILL ANALYZE THE VARIABILITY OF THESE OBJECTS ON TIMESCALES RANGING FROM HOURS TO MONTHS IN ORDER TO MODEL THE ACCRETION ONTO THE STAR  DETECT DISK DENSITY VARIATIONS  MEASURE ROTATION RATES  AND SEARCH FOR ECLIPSING/TRANSITING COMPANIONS. THE RESULTS OF OUR ANALYSIS WILL LEAD TO A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE RANGE OF CONDITIONS UNDER WHICH PLANETARY SYSTEMS FORM. THE PROPOSED WORK USES THE UNIQUE CAPABILITIES OF K2 TO COLLECT DATA WITH THE PRECISION  DURATION  AND DUTY CYCLE NEEDED FOR SUCH A STUDY.

award_description:
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
VOLUNTEERS OF AMERICA (VOA) IS A NATIONAL, FAITH-BASED HUMAN SERVICE ORGANIZATION WITH 36 AFFILIATES ACROSS THE US INCLUDING WESTERN WASHINGTON. FOR OVER 100 YEARS, VOLUNTEERS OF AMERICA HAS PROVIDED HIGH QUALITY SERVICES IN THE PUGET SOUND REGION. OUR MISSION IS TO SERVE PEOPLE AND COMMUNITIES IN NEED AND CREATE OPPORTUNITIES FOR PEOPLE TO EXPERIENCE THE JOY OF SERVING OTHERS. TO ACCOMPLISH OUR MISSION, VOAWW IS COMMITTED TO DELIVERING QUALITY PROGRAMS THAT UTILIZE VOLUNTEERS AND ASSIST PEOPLE IN LEADING A MORE SATISFYING, QUALITY LIFE. EACH YEAR MORE THAN 350,000 PEOPLE CONTACT VOAWW FOR SERVICES. VOAWW HAS A HISTORY OF PROVIDING SERVICES FOR SENIORS. AS A SPONSOR AGENCY FOR THE CNCS FUNDED SENIOR COMPANION PROGRAM, WE ALSO HAVE A STRONG UNDERSTANDING OF REGULATIONS GUIDING SENIOR CORPS PROGRAMS. 
VOAWW OPERATES SIX PROGRAMS IN SKAGIT COUNTY -- RSVP, NORTHSOUND 211, CARE CRISIS RESPONSE SERVICES (A REGIONAL MENTAL HEALTH CRISIS LINE), THE DISPUTE RESOLUTION CENTER OF SKAGIT COUNTY, DISABILITY SERVICES (SERVING ADULTS WITH INTELLECTUAL DISABILITIES) AND YOUTH AND CHILD DEVELOPMENT SERVICES. SKAGIT COUNTY IS A COUNTY IN WASHINGTON STATE, NAMED AFTER THE SKAGIT INDIAN TRIBE. AS OF THE 2010 CENSUS, THE POPULATION WAS 116,901. IT IS INCLUDED IN THE MOUNT VERNON-ANACORTES, WASHINGTON, AND METROPOLITAN STATISTICAL AREA. THE SKAGIT MARITIME VALLEY HAS OVER 93,000 ACRES OF ACTIVE FARMLAND. THE SKAGIT RIVER COMPRISES THE THIRD LARGEST WATERSHED ON THE WEST COAST OF THE CONTINENTAL UNITED STATES WITH A DELTA GRACED BY WORKING FARMS AND WILDLIFE REFUGES. THE SKAGIT FLATS IS ONE OF THE MOST POPULAR AREAS FOR BIRDING IN WASHINGTON STATE. THE VALLEY'S CULTURE IS RICH IN FARMING, FISHING, NATURE, AND ART.
AN ESTIMATED 700 RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL SERVE IN SKAGIT COUNTY THROUGH THIS GRANT. SOME OF THE ACTIVITIES WILL INCLUDE: TRAIL MAINTENANCE, FOOD DISTRIBUTION, TUTORING, BUILDING HOMES, BLOOD DRIVES, AND VACATION HOME CHECKS. THE PRIMARY FOCUS AREA OF THIS PROJECT IS HEALTHY FUTURES. IN A COMMUNITY KNOWN FOR ITS AGRICULTURAL ABUNDANCE, THE HIGHEST RISK FOR PREMATURE DEATH IS THE LACK OF FRESH FRUITS AND VEGETABLES. 75.3% OF THE ADULTS IN SKAGIT COUNTY REPORT EATING LESS THAN 5 SERVINGS OF FRUITS AND VEGETABLES PER DAY (COMMUNITY STATUS RISK INDICATORS, US DEPT. OF HHS, 2013).
POVERTY IS CLOSELY LINKED TO HUNGER AND FOOD INSECURITY. HAVING THE RESOURCES TO OBTAIN NECESSARY FOOD IS CRITICAL TO REDUCING HUNGER AND FOOD INSECURITY. IN FACT, FEDERAL POVERTY GUIDELINES ARE THE DETERMINING FACTOR FOR MANY FOOD PROGRAMS, INCLUDING FOOD STAMPS AND FREE AND REDUCED LUNCHES FOR SCHOOL AGE CHILDREN. NOT HAVING THE RESOURCES TO OBTAIN FOOD IS ONE OF THE PRIMARY REASONS PEOPLE SKIP MEALS AND SLIP FROM FOOD INSECURITY INTO HUNGER. THIS IS WHY CONNECTING RSVP VOLUNTEERS WITH MEANINGFUL WAYS TO SERVE IS SO VITAL. 
AT THE END OF THE THREE-YEAR GRANT, WE ANTICIPATE THAT RECRUITING AND PLACING VOLUNTEERS IN THESE AREAS WILL HELP INCREASE THE CAPACITY OF LOCAL ORGANIZATIONS THAT ADDRESS HUNGER AND FOOD INSECURITY ISSUES. RSVP VOLUNTEERS WILL ENABLE THESE ORGANIZATIONS, SUCH AS MEALS-ON-WHEELS PROGRAMS, FOOD BANKS, FOOD PANTRIES AND COMMUNITY GARDENS TO INCREASE FOOD SECURITY AND REDUCE HUNGER IN SKAGIT COUNTY.

award_description: THE SOUTH DAKOTA SPACE GRANT CONSORTIUM (SDSGC) AND ITS PARTNERS ARE WILLING AND READY TO JOIN NASA IN ITS EFFORTS TO INSPIRE AMERICA'S NEXT GENERATION OF EXPLORERS AND INNOVATORS. SOUTH DAKOTA IS FULL OF EAGER  BRIGHT  CREATIVE  HARD-WORKING CHILDREN WHO HAVE GREAT POTENTIAL TO BECOME THE "HIGHLY EDUCATED AND WELL-PREPARED WORKFORCE" THAT WILL EFFECTIVELY MANAGE AND LEAD THE NATION'SLABORATORIES AND RESEARCH CENTERS OF TOMORROW.  TO HELP SOUTH DAKOTA'S LOW-INCOME  MINORITY AND FEMALE MIDDLE SCHOOL STUDENTS HAVE EQUAL ACCESS TO THESE DREAMS THAT SOLID STEM EDUCATION CAN PREPARE THEM FOR  THE SDSGC AND THE SD DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION 21ST CENTURY COMMUNITY LEARNING CENTER PROGRAM (CCLC) PROPOSES SD SUMMERS OF INNOVATION AS A PLAN TO BUILD A STATEWIDE NETWORK THAT WILL LINK ORGANIZATIONS WITH STEM RESOURCES AND THE LOCAL CCLC'S THAT SERVE THE HIGH-POVERTY CHILDREN OF OUR STATE.AS A TEAM  THE SD SOI PARTNERS WILL BUILD THE CAPACITY OF COMMUNITY AND SCHOOL-BASED ORGANIZATIONS TO ENGAGE UNDERSERVED STUDENTS IN HIGH QUALITY STEM CONTENT IN SUMMER AND EXTENDED LEARNING EXPERIENCES TAILORED TO MEET LOCAL NEEDS. SD SOI WILL SUPPORT THE INFUSION OF NASA THEMES AND RESOURCES IN SUMMER AND EXTENDED LEARNING ENVIRONMENTS. AND  THIS PROJECT WILL FACILITATE THE ALIGNMENTOF SUMMER AND EXTENDED PROGRAMMING WITH THE FORMAL EDUCATION COMMUNITY TO SUPPORT COORDINATED AND SUSTAINED ENGAGEMENT IN STEM CONTENT.  TO ACCOMPLISH THESE GOALS  SD SOI WILL START BY PROVIDING SCIENCE  TECHNOLOGY  ENGINEERING AND MATHEMATICS PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENTTO OVER 150 CERTIFIED MIDDLE SCHOOL TEACHERS AND CCLC STAFF MEMBERS. AT LEAST 2000 STUDENTS WILL PARTICIPATE IN 40 OR MORE HOURS OF STEM ACTIVITIES IN CAMPS CONDUCTED BY THE NEWLY TRAINED TEACHERS. AT LEAST ANOTHER FIVE HUNDRED STUDENTS WILL PARTICIPATE IN CAMPS BROUGHT TO THEIR CCLC SITE BY SCIENCE MUSEUMS OR HELD IN UNIVERSITY SETTINGS ACROSS THE STATE. SCHOLARSHIPS AND TRAVEL STIPENDS WILL BEPROVIDED TO INCREASE THE ACCESSIBILITY OF THESE OPPORTUNITIES.  THE TRAINED TEACHERS WILL BE SUPPORTED IN THEIR EFFORTS BY A SD SOI TEACHER COORDINATOR WHO WILL LINK THEM TO LOW AND NO COST RESOURCES AND PEOPLE THAT WILL AID THEIR EFFORTS TO INFUSE NASA CONTENT INTO THE FORMAL EDUCATION ENVIRONMENT.  THROUGH THEIR CCLC AFTERSCHOOL PROGRAMS  ROBOTICS TEAMS  STARLAB AND GEODOME PROGRAMS  STEM EVENTS AND NEW OPPORTUNITIES OFFERED BY THEIR CLASSROOM TEACHERS  OVER 2500 SOUTH DAKOTA MIDDLE SCHOOL STUDENTS WILL PARTICIPATE IN EXTENDED LEARNING OPPORTUNITIESTHAT WILL EXPOSE THEM EACH TO TWENTY-FIVE ADDITIONAL HOURS OF STEM-BASED LEARNING.  A KEY OUTCOME OF THIS PROJECT WILL BE THE ESTABLISHMENT OF TIGHTLY CONNECTED NETWORK OF PARTNERS JOINED TOGETHER TO MEET THE STEM NEEDS OF SOUTH DAKOTA STUDENTS. THIS NETWORK CAN SERVE AS A LAUNCH POINT AND MODEL FOR ACHIEVING FUTURE GOALS.
